Define the toy model used for quantitative validation: (i) the particle- particle- irreducible electronic vertex $ ar{\Gamma}^{\mathrm{e}}$ is approximated by the dynamically screened Coulomb interaction treated in RPA, $W_{\mathrm{RPA}}(\mathbf{q},
u) = v_{\mathbf{q}}/(1 - v_{\mathbf{q}}\Pi^{0}_{\mathbf{q}
u})$, where $v_{\mathbf{q}}=4\pi e^{2}/q^{2}$ and $\Pi^{0}$ is the noninteracting polarization; (ii) the phonon- mediated interaction $W^{\mathrm{ph}}_{q
u}$ is taken from a model form $$ W_{q
u}^{\mathrm{ph}} = - rac{g/N_{F}}{1 + (q/2k_{F})^{2}} rac{\omega_{q}^{2}}{
u^{2} + \omega_{q}^{2}}, $$ with $\omega_{q}^{2}=\omega_{D}^{2}(q/k_{F})^{2}/(1+(q/k_{F})^{2})$ and coupling strength $g=0.4$ (as used in the paper); these choices produce a conservative, representative model of conventional metal screening plus a realistic phonon kernel. [23]

Present representative numerical results and benchmarking against experiment from the paper (these are outputs of the above procedure using computed DFPT $\lambda$ and interpolated VDiagMC $\mu_{E_{F}}$ and are reported in Table II, Fig. 10–11):
- Aluminum (ambient pressure): predicted $T_{c}^{\mathrm{EFT}}\approx 0.96\,$K vs experimental $1.2\,$K (good agreement within uncertainty);
- Zinc: predicted $T_{c}^{\mathrm{EFT}}\approx 0.874\,$K vs experimental $0.875\,$K (near exact match);
- Lithium (hcp): predicted $T_{c}^{\mathrm{EFT}}\approx 0.03\,$K vs reported experimental $4\times 10^{-4}\,$K (discrepancy noted; structural uncertainties in Li at very low $T$ are discussed);
- Sodium and Magnesium: predicted $T_{c}$ values are extremely small (practically zero within current experimental reach);
- Potassium: predicted nonsuperconducting in the computed conditions.
Report that these predictions substantially reduce prior uncertainties for sub- Kelvin superconductors and reconcile theory with experiment in benchmark cases.
